    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Paint created by mixing dry pigments with molten wax, usually beeswax. Sometimes small amounts of natural resins, such as dammar or Venice turpentine, are added for hardness. Oils, such as linseed oil, are added for increased workability. Encaustic paint was used as early as the 4th and 5th centuries BCE in Greece. The paint was applied warm with a spatula or brush. It hardened quickly and fused to the surface. </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047822/MFA Conservation and Art Material Encyclopedia Online: CAMEO (2005-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Pintura creada mezclando pigmentos con cera fundida y refinada y resina. Se aplica mientras está tibia en los paneles o murales con brocha o paleta, y se fija pasando una fuente de calor sobre la superficie para que se funda y quede permanentemente unida a la pintura.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Verf die wordt gemaakt door droge pigmenten te vermengen met gesmolten, geraffineerde was en hars. Het wordt warm aangebracht op panelen of muren met een borstel of een spatel en gefixeerd door met een warmtebron over het oppervlak te gaan om de verf permanent te smelten en vast te zetten.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099640/RKD thesaurus</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>一種混合乾燥顏料與熔化精煉的蠟和樹脂所製成的顏料。在顏料尚微溫時用畫筆或調色工具塗抹至畫板或牆壁上，之後用熱物質覆蓋畫表面，使其熔合並凝固，顏料才能永久黏合。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Tinta criada pela mistura de pigmentos secos com cera fundida, geralmente cera de abelha. Às vezes, pequenas quantidades de resinas naturais, como dammar ou terebintina de Veneza, são adicionadas para dar dureza. Óleos, como óleo de linhaça, são adicionados para aumentar a trabalhabilidade. A tinta encáustica foi usada já nos séculos 4 e 5 aC na Grécia. A tinta foi aplicada quente com uma espátula ou pincel. Endureceu rapidamente e se fundiu à superfície. </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000316/CVAA-BR</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109633/CVAA-BR Consortium (2020-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
